instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle follows a Model‑Based Systems‑Engineering (MBSE) disciplined pathway comprising four abstraction layers: (1) requirements abstraction, where stakeholder needs are captured in system–level requirement documents; (2) functional architecture, described with SysML use‑case and activity diagrams and refined in component‑connector diagrams such as ADL snippets from ACME or SysML IBDs; (3) logical architecture, developed with architectural description languages (ADLs) like MontiArc or AADL automata that capture behavioral aspects; and (4) product/technical layers, where concrete implementation models are specified using code generators or Simulink block diagrams. Transition management between layers is governed by RFLP (Requirements‑Functions‑Logics‑Physics) methodology, ensuring traceability of functional intent through to physical entities. Lifecycle governance is performed with MBSE tools that support model versioning, change‑impact analysis, and artifact linking across the four layers."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "Standard compliance is achieved by adhering to open modeling standards: SysML v1.7 for functional and structural modeling, AADL for architecture description with real‑time properties, MontiArc for component‑connector behavioral modeling, and ACME for extensible architectural notation. These ADLs ensure interoperability with industry toolchains such as Enterprise Architect or Cameo, and provide mapping mechanisms to IEC 61131‑3 code templates for further implementation."
]
